e I recognize? If I can't tell, I just move on. I think the biggest thing for people like me who aren't constantly online is to not feel pressured to engage with everything we see. Just because something pops up on your feed doesn't mean you need to react to it or pass it along. I've seen people get really worked up over things that turned out to be completely false, and that kind of stress isn't worth it. My part-time cleaning job keeps me busy enough without adding social media drama to my life. When I'm home, I'd rather spend time baking or listening to classical music than getting caught up in online arguments about things that might not even be true. I wish the platforms themselves would do more to stop fake content before it reaches people, but until then, I think we all just need to slow down, think twice, and not believe everything we read online. It's about protecting your peace of mind and not contributing to the problem by spreading things you're not sure about.","reasoning_summary":"The persona spends minimal time on social media (few times monthly), has low openness suggesting preference for familiar approaches, moderate extraversion indicating some social engagement but not excessive, anxious psychological feature meaning concern about misinformation effects, Islamic beliefs emphasizing truth and honesty, no formal education suggesting practical rather than technical approach, part-time cleaner occupation indicating working-class perspective, married suggesting consultation with spouse, hobbies of classical music and baking indicating preference for offline activities. Combined these traits to create a cautious, practical, values-driven perspective that acknowledges limitations while emphasizing common sense, personal peace, and not contributing to misinformation spread. Tone is conversational, honest, slightly worried but measured, reflecting moderate agreeableness and the anxious feature without being overwhelmed.","tone":"conversational, honest, pra